The paper deals with the analysis of the performance of the orthogonal matching pursuit (OMP) algorithm for sparse recovery, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of compressed sensing (cs.SP) and signal processing (cs.SI). The analysis relies on the restricted isometry property (RIP), which is a concept from information theory (cs.IT) that has been extensively used in compressed sensing. The paper also presents a new result that improves upon earlier analyses of OMP, which suggests that it may be of interest to the machine learning community (cs.LG). Finally, the paper involves mathematical analysis and optimization, which are topics that are relevant to numerical analysis (cs.NA).
